Length ball, angling in from middle. Sam Billings flicks it towards deep mid-wicket and settles for a single.
Good-length ball, well outside off. Billings does not offer any shot to this one.
Scott Boland (11-6-17-1) to resume from the other end.
FOUR! Lovely timing and placement from Woakes! Green serves a full ball, around middle. Woakes prods and just eases it past the mid on fielder to bag a boundary.
Short of a length, around middle. Sam Billings tucks it with soft hands to the on side for a run. England are underway in the last session.
Full ball, outside off. Sam Billings drives it back to the bowler who half-stops it and the ball goes towards mid off.
Good-length ball, jagging back in sharply from outside off. Sam Billings stays back to defend but he misses and gets hit on his thigh pad. A stifled appeal for LBW but the umpire shakes his head.
BEATEN! Good-length ball, outside off and nipping away a bit. Billings looks to block but the ball goes past his blade.
Green starts with a back-of-a-length delivery, around off. Billings gets right behind the line of the ball to block it.

Right then, we are back for the final session on Day 2. Australia right on top of the proceedings and they stride out to the middle looking positive. Sam Billings also powers back onto the field and looks ready for the challenge. Chris Woakes is out behind him. Cameron Green (7-0-29-0) to start off with the ball after the break.
... Day 2, Session 3 ...

It was Australia's skipper, Pat Cummins who carried on in his merry way after the Dinner break and got rid of Joe Root and Dawid Malan just when both of these batters were looking settled in the middle. There was a passage of play where England lost 3 wickets for just 7 runs and that tells us the whole story. The ever-so impressive Scott Boland did what he is best known far - he got rid of Ollie Pope with a peach of a delivery and England were in all sorts of trouble. However, things could have been much worse for the visitors had the slip cordon been tighter. Woakes was dropped on a couple of occasions off Scott Boland, David Warner and Usman Khawaja being the culprit. All in all, it was a top session for Australia and they will now look to get the remaining wickets quickly once the play resumes after Tea break. Sam Billings has looked good in the middle and he would hope that he doesn't run out of partners if England are to stage a comeback in this Test. Do join us for the last session of the day which promises to be a cracking one. It will begin at 2.30 pm IST (9 am GMT).

A session that has been dominated by the Aussies and this Test is moving ahead at a rate of knots. The same old story continues for England, the top order fails to deliver and then Root and Malan do the repair work. However, both Root and Malan have failed to capitalize on the start that they got and once again in the series, the English side is on the back foot. They did manage to score 90 runs in the session but have lost 4 wickets as well.
Woakes survives. Boland goes full and outside off, inviting the drive but Woakes times it sweetly towards cover. Tea is taken with England reeling at 124/6!
Good-length ball, on off and solid block off the front foot by Woakes.
Trying to nip it back in from wide outside off. The ball does come back a bit but Woakes leaves it alone.
Boland pulls his length back and bowls it around off. Woakes hops and gets behind the line of the ball to block it out.
Boland goes full and wide. Woakes doesn't play at it.

DROPPED! That is poor! Khawaja should have left Smith take it! Full and wide outside off. Woakes goes for the drive away from his body but gets the outside edge. Now, the ball flies to the slip cordon. Mark Waugh has been saying for a while now that the slips are too close together and that could be an issue. Now, Khawaja, who is at third slip, moves to his left side. Natural side for him so there's that. But he goes right in front of Smith, who is at second slip to take it. Smith could have easily taken that to his right with minimal movement but Khawaja goes for it and drops it!
Length ball, around off. Billings gets the outside edge towards the slip cordon.
Banged in short, on middle. Woakes taps it towards square leg for one.
Fuller, on middle. Woakes looks to work it away but gets the leading edge towards cover.
Cameron Green goes agonizingly past the outside edge again! He pitches it up, just outside off. Woakes is glued to the crease as he looks to block but the ball zips past the bat.
Back of a length, on off. Woakes hops up to block it.
Length ball, shapes away after landing outside off. Left alone.
On a length, around off. Blocked out.
Length but wide enough for Billings to leave it with ease.
On a length, on off. Blocked out.
Full, lands outside off and comes back in. Billings is hit on the pads while looking to flick.
FOUR! Length ball, around off. Billings gets the outside edge towards third man again. It goes past the cordon and runs to the fence.

Length and down the leg side. Billings gets hit on the pads while looking to flick. There is an appeal but only by two players. The first one is the bowler and the second one is the man at first slip. That could be Marnus Labuschagne!
Length ball, around off. Pushed away by Woakes.

Mark Waugh and Michael Hussey think that there should be one more slip brought in. Currently, there are two of them but they reckon there should be one more. They talk about how Steven Smith who is himself in the slips was gesturing to Cummins that there should be reinforcements brought in the cordon.
Beaten! Full, just outside off. Woakes goes for the drive but is beaten.
Short and down the leg side. Woakes leaves it alone.
FOUR! Well played. On a length, around off. Woakes plays it with soft hands past second slip for a boundary.
Beaten! Length ball, just outside off. Woakes looks to block it from the crease but it shapes away and goes past the bat.
Fuller, on off. Blocked out.
On a length, on off. Pushed past point. Billings thinks of the single for a second but decides against it in the end.
Nice and full, around off. Sam gets forward to block.
Beaten! That is the perfect delivery! Length ball, quite close to the off pole so Billings has to play at it. But the ball holds its line and goes past the outside edge.
Good-length ball, outside off and curling away late. Sam Billings has a tentative poke at it but the ball goes past his outside edge.
A bit closer to the off pole and nice away shape on that. Left alone yet again.
Nice and full, but wide enough for Billings to leave it with ease.
Bumper, on off. Woakes sits under it.
Short of a length, on the body. Billings works it off the bottom edge, through square leg for a single.
FOUR! That is nicely played by Billings! Short of a length, outside off. He gets on his toes and punches it past covers for a boundary.
Length ball, on off. Blocked to mid on by Billings.
On a length, outside off. Left alone.
Full, outside off. Billings gets the inside edge on the pads.

Dropped! My word, David Warner has dropped a dolly. Boland almost had two in two and he really should have. Another lovely away-shaping delivery from Boland. Woakes is forced to play at it and gets the outside edge. The ball goes to Warner at first slip and it is at a comfortable height but he spills it.
Chris Woakes is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Scott Boland is just relentless and does get the breakthrough. Boland pitches it a bit further up and keeps the ball in the channel around off. Ollie Pope is forced into pressing forward and he does so, looking to push it out wide. The ball shapes away after pitching and the outside edge is taken. Alex Carey moves to his right and takes an easy catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Scott Boland

Commentary.Commentary: This is angled in on middle and Pope pushes it out towards mid on.
Length again, keeping it close to the off stump. Pope shoulders arms.
The ball is moving a bit here. Around off and well left by Pope.
Lovely away shape. Boland is always on song. A length ball, outside off and inviting the drive. Pope goes for it but gets well beaten.
Scott Boland (7-3-13-0) is back on.
Lands on a length, wide outside off and comes back in sharply. Billings gets hit on the body while looking to block.
On a length, on the pads. Worked to fine leg for a single.
A short one, down the leg side. Pope leaves it and Carey moves to his left to gather it.
What happened there? This lands on a length, wide outside off and comes back in very sharply. Pope leaves it alone but gets hit high on the pads.
FOUR! Beautifully played! Length, on middle. Pope shuffles a tiny bit and flicks it past mid on for a boundary.
Short of a length, outside off. Pope leaves it at the last moment. The ball bounces on its way to the keeper.
Oooh! Length and just outside off. Billings decides to leave it a bit too late. The ball hits the toe end and goes towards the slip cordon.
Back of a length, on off. Billings blocks from back on the deck.
Length ball, on the pads. Billings looks to flick it away but gets hit high on the pads.
Back of a length, on off. Tapped out. A solid defence and a 'no run!' from Billings.
Tap and run. Length ball, on off. Pope shuffles across and taps it to the leg side for a quick single.
Full, just outside off. Blocked out.
Length, on off. Tapped towards gully and a few Aussie fielders get a bit chirpy.
FOUR! And again! This is lovely bowling from Billings! Full again, around off. He drives it handsomely to the long off for one.
FOUR! Oh, top shot! A bit overpitched and outside off. Billings drives it uppishly but past mid off for a boundary.
Fuller, on off. Tapped to gully.
Jaffa! This is lovely bowling from Cummins! Billings is once again beaten while looking to block due to the hint of away shape. It has gotten a bit overcast and that should help the pacers.
Beaten again! Now, Billings is facing the music! Length ball, just outside off. Billings looks to block but the ball holds its line and goes past the outside edge.
And again! This is a bit closer to the off pole but angling away. Pope is glued to the crease while looking to block and it goes past the outside edge.
Oh beaten! This lands on the fourth stump and goes on with the angle. Pope is beaten as he looks to block.
Lovely from Sam Billings. He gets off the mark and has a little giggle with the umpire saying, "At least I'm off mate." Good to see a guy relaxed on Test debut, that too in the Ashes.
FOUR! Brilliant again. Starc overcompensates and bowls it full, on the pads. Pope whips it past mid on for a boundary.
FOUR! Top shot! Overpitched and outside off. Pope nicely drives it past covers for a boundary.
Full, on off. Blocked out.
Short of a length, down the leg side. Pope leaves it alone.
Nice and full, on off. Billings gets forward to block it.
Billings is off the mark! His first runs in Test cricket! Full, on the pads. He works it wide of deep backward square leg for a couple.
'NO RUN!' yells Sam Billings as he blocks this length ball, on off. Must be a good feeling to hit your first ball in Tests from the middle of the bat.
Length and on the pads. Pope gets it towards fine leg for a single.
Length, lands on middle and angles down the leg side. Pope looks to work it away but misses.
Length ball, on off. Pope blocks but gets it off the inner half to mid-wicket.
Sam Billings, on debut, comes out to bat with England in a spot of real bother.

OUT! TAKEN! That is a top catch from the GOAT at backward point. England are falling like a pack of cards now and the Aussies are all over the tourists! This was a short-of-a-length delivery, just outside off. Stokes hangs back and cuts hard but finds Nathan Lyon at backward point who moves to his left quickly, gets low and takes a very good low catch. Stokes stands there in disbeleif and then makes his way back to the pavilion.
Commentary.Howout: c Nathan Lyon b Mitchell Starc

Commentary.Commentary: Full-length ball, outside off. Ben Stokes squeezes it out towards mid on.

FOUR! Jeez! That could have been the fifth one for the Aussies! This was a good-length ball, angling in from middle. Stokes looks to flick it but he gets a tickle on it and the ball goes past the diving leg slip fielder for a boundary.
On a length, around off. Ben Stokes gets behind the line of the ball to block it out.
Good-length ball, outside off. Ben Stokes shoulders his arms to this one.
Short of a length, well outside off. Ben Stokes lets it sail through to the keeper.
Full ball, outside off. Ollie Pope pushes it back to the bowler.
Good-length ball, around middle and leg. Ollie Pope tucks it towards mid-wicket.
Ollie Pope comes out to face an on-song Pat Cummins.

OUT! LBW! The Aussie skipper gets rid of the English skipper and England are in deep, deep trouble now! This is a length ball, just outside off and nipping back in sharply. Root stays back, hops in his crease to flick it away but misses and gets rapped in front. Cummins appeals and the umpire raises his dreaded finger in no time. Root is not even bothered with a prolonged discussion as to whether he should take the review or not. He walks away simply after having a word with his partner. Huge moment in this Test match as England's most dependable batter, Joe Root walks back to the hut.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Pat Cummins

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller in length, around middle. Joe Root drives it towards mid on.
Back of a length, coming in with the angle from outside off. Joe Root stays back to block but he misses and gets hit on his thigh pad.
Length ball, on off. Joe Root drives it back to the bowler.

Swing and a miss! Length ball, well outside off. Ben Stokes throws his bat at it but fails to connect. There might have been a faint edge on that and there was a noise. But regardless, it didn't carry to the keeper.
Good-length ball, around middle. Ben Stokes nudges it towards square leg.
Starc errs in line this time and sprays it down leg. Ben Stokes misses his flick and the ball goes through to the keeper.
Starc drags his length back a bit, around middle. Joe Root gets back in his crease and tucks it wide of the mid-wicket fielder for a single.
Good-length ball, angling across the batter from outside off. Joe Root stays back and offers no shot to this one.

A length ball, around leg. Joe Root glances it wide of the fine leg fielder. Scott Boland there moves across to his right and cuts it off just in front of the ropes. The batters collect a couple of runs. A huge round of applause for Boland as he stops the ball. He is someone who can do no wrong in the series and these scenes were seen in Sydney too. What a start for him in Test cricket!
Fuller in length this time, outside off. Ben Stokes leaves it alone for the keeper to collect.
Back of a length, around off. Ben Stokes gets behind the line of the ball to defend it.
Ben Stokes is in at number 5.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Oh, dear! A wicket against the run of play and Malan would not believe his luck here! He gets strangled down the leg side. This is a length ball, angling in from leg. Malan looks to flick but he only manages a tickle to the right of the keeper. Alex Carey moves there and pouches it with ease. Huge blow this for England as these two were looking quite good in the middle.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Pat Cummins

Commentary.Commentary: Good-length ball, around off. Root taps it to the off side and scampers through to the other end.
Top delivery from the skipper! This is a yorker-length ball, around off. Root looks to dig it out and gets an inside edge onto his pad. Had there been no bat involved, Root was a goner!

Big Bash League News - Mitchell Marsh, Josh Inglis, Mitchell Swepson and Michael Neser have been released from the Australian men's Test squad to return to the Big Bash League and join their respective clubs. Swepson and Neser will join Brisbane Heat and Marsh, along with Inglis will strengthen Perth Scorchers even further. The four will take a charter flight from Hobart to Melbourne tomorrow. Marcus Harris and Jhye Richardson will remain in Hobart for the remainder of the fifth Test match.
Back of a length, around off. Joe Root stays back and taps it towards backward point.
FOUR! Nicely done! Fuller in length, outside off. Malan lunges forward and caresses it through the cover region. The ball races away to the fence.
On a length, on off. Dawid Malan blocks it out.
Length ball, around leg. Joe Root flicks it through the mid-wicket region. The fielder there gives it a chase and cuts it off. The batters take three runs.

Ooh, that looks close and yes, Pat Cummins does go for the review for LBW. UltraEdge is up and it is confirmed that there's no bat involved. Ball Tracker shows that the impact is umpire's call, just around off and the ball is missing the top of off by centimeters. The onfield decision stands and Australia lose a review.

NOT OUT! Joe Root SURVIVES! This was a good-length ball, just outside off and shaping away a bit after landing. Root looks to drive it down the ground but he misses and gets hit on his pad. Starc puts in an appeal but the umpire says no. Cummins opts for a review but the Ball Tracker suggests that the impact is umpire's call and wickets missing.
Length ball, around middle and leg. Joe Root flicks it off his pads and collects a couple of runs.
FOUR! GLORIOUS! Starc starts with a half-volley, outside off. Root lunges forward and caresses it through the cover region to fetch himself a boundary.
Mitchell Starc (3-1-12-0) comes back to bowl.
FOUR! Gets it through does Malan and it's yet another boundary for the visitors. A touch shorter and outside off. Malan hangs back and just guides it past backward point for a boundary.
Assured leave this time from Dawid Malan. Good-length ball, around off and left alone.
Oi, that was closer than Malan thought. This one shapes in beautifully from outside off and Malan leaves it on line. The ball ends up going just past the off stump.
Misfield from Marnus. A length ball, on off and Joe Root punches it firmly towards covers. Marnus doesn't collect it cleanly and the batters get one.
Green goes a bit fuller and keeps it close to the off pole. Root edges it down with soft hands towards gully.
A bit of yes and no but no damage done. Back of a length, around off. Root drops it on the off side and looks for the quick single but Malan sends him back and rightly so.
Angled in at off from 'round the wicket. Malan stays solid in defense.
Back of a length, around off. Root hangs back and eases it on the off side for a single.
This one nips back in from off stump. Root is caught on the crease a bit but does well to keep it out.
A length ball, wide of off stump. Left alone by Root.

FOUR! Just eased through the off side. Boland pitches it up and the ball shapes away. Root though leans in and drives it beautifully through covers for another boundary. The runs are flowing a bit here for England.
In that channel around off and angling it in at around 137 kph. Joe Root makes an assured leave.
On a good length, around off and cut away towards point.
FOUR! Green needs to be a bit more patient here. He offers width and Malan duly obliges. Shortish ball, outside off and this is slapped through point for a boundary.
Full again, trying to attack the pads but Malan eases it towards mid on.
Slightly fuller this time from Green and around off. Malan stands tall and strokes it towards cover-point. The fielder over there dives to his left to make a good stop.
Length again, a bit wide of off stump and left alone by Malan.
On a good length, around the off pole. Root goes on the back foot to tuck it away leg side but gets an inside edge past square leg and they get through for a single.
BEATEN! Another top delivery from Boland! Good-length delivery, outside off and jagging back in late. Malan stays back to block but he misses as the ball goes past his outside edge.
On off. Blocked out.
Boland is bowling a lovely length here. Around off, angling in and Malan looks to play it out with soft hands. He gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Short of a good length, over middle. Root pushes it off the back foot towards mid-wicket for a quick single.
FOUR! Lovely timing from Joe Root. This is angled into the pads and Root just tucks it through square leg and finds the boundary.
Good-length ball, outside off and shaping away nicely. Root hangs back and looks to push it through covers but gets beaten past the outside edge.
Inside edge on the pads! Short of a length, outside off. Malan looks to punch it away but gets the inside edge back on the pads.
Back of a length, outside off. Malan steers it to gully.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.

Noise as the ball goes past the bat! Australia decide not to review it though. Oh boy, there is a spike as the ball goes past the bat on UltraEdge and Justin Langer cannot believe it! The ball is far away from the pad and even the bat hasn't brushed the pads! This lands on off, on a length. Malan looks to block but leaves a gap between his bat and pad. The ball goes through that gap and goes to the keeper. There is an appeal for caught behind but the umpire is not interested. Cummins has a word with his bowler but decides not to review this. Australia could have had their third! Cummins probably thought that it hit the pad and Carey wasn't too excited either. Green was the most excited but couldn't convince his skipper to take the review.
FOUR! No stopping that one! Full, outside off. Malan drives it past covers for a boundary.
Runs for Root! Full, on off. He works it past mid-wicket. Two fielders chase it. Cummins slides and drags it back in. While the other one throws it back. Three runs.
Back of a length, just outside off. There is a bit of extra bounce on that and Malan takes his hand off the bat while looking to block. It goes towards point.
Boland goes on the pads now. Malan gets hit on the pads while looking to block.
Boland drags his length back a bit but keeps bowling it quite wide outside off. Malan prods forwards but leaves it yet again.
Full and outside off. Left alone.
Lands fuller, outside off and comes back in with the angle. Malan shoulders his arms.
Length, on off. Blocked out.

Beaten! Ohhs and ahhs from the slip cordon as this one goes just past the outside edge! Green serves a length ball, in the corridor outside off. It shapes away just enough to go past Root's attempted defence.
Green bowls it full, on off. Blocked out by Root.
A bit shorter and wider. Root pushes it to cover.
Length ball, angling back in from off. Root works it past square leg for a couple.
Better. Length ball, just outside off. Root is forced to play at it and he blocks it.
Length ball, down the leg side. Root lets Carey collect it.
Who will start with the ball from the other end? It is Cameron Green.
Boland bowls it fuller, on off. Malan drives it nicely to mid off.
Length, on the pads. Root works it past square leg for a single.
A bit shorter and wider outside off. Root leaves it alone.
Fuller, around off. Root blocks it well.
Nice and full, on off. Root pushes it to mid on.
Boland is right on the money after the break. He bowls a length ball, on off. Root stays in the crease to block it.

Ah well, back to Hobart then! Can England bat well in this batting-friendly session? Or will Australia continue to pick wickets at regular intervals? The sun is going down but by no means, are these twilight conditions. The visitors have two full hours of excellent batting conditions. Out come the players. It will be Scott Boland vs Joe Root first up. Here we go...
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

South Africa are all set to resume their home season after Covid hit them pretty badly. The pandemic has not been kind on anybody but the Proteas seem to have been hurt the most, with their domestic season being hit for two years in a row. International cricket at home was also a big question mark, with series not getting staged completely or being abandoned. However, with every country slowly recovering, the rainbow nation too, is planning and hoping to do the same. The first step is the rescheduling of cancelled tours in the past 2 years. England were supposed to play a full-staged tour in 2020-2021 but abandoned the tour midway due to Covid concerns while Australia, who were supposed to tour this nation in March 2021, pulled out too. Both those tours have been rescheduled for 2023. The Proteas play the Aussies in August 2023, while England will have a winter tour in the same year. Good for the home side. Thanks to India visiting them, their financial crisis would have been resolved to some extent.

More Ashes problems for the English. Oh dear, as if the current situation was not bad enough. With the Men's Ashes coming to a close, we focus on the females, who shall be contesting their Ashes from Thursday, 20th January, 2022. However, Covid issues in the England camp forced the schedule to be rejigged and the result is their captain openly admitting to concerns and anxieties within the camp. This has come with the latest news - a staff member within the English camp has tested positive for Covid-19. With the first practice session also washed out, captain Heather Knight has termed their build-up so far as pretty average. However, more than the lack of cricket, it is the mental aspect which would be worrying for the visitors. We all know what Steven Smith was going through last year, when he was in continuous bio bubbles. Let's hope that England find mental relaxation quickly and we get a good competitive Women's Ashes.

NO CHARGES AGAINST INDIA. Well, after all the drama at Newlands, Cape Town, set up by a controversially overturned dismissal of Dean Elgar on Day 3 of the third Test between South Africa and India, due to a possible DRS bust-up, the decision by the match officials is that no charges have been levied against the visiting team. One could understand the frustration in the Indian camp after Elgar, who was adjudged LBW by umpire Marais Erasmus off Ashwin, got a reprieve by Ball Tracker, projecting the ball to go over the stumps. That looked so unbelievable that even Erasmus could be hutted muttering his disbelief over the stump mic. However, with anger set in, a few Indian players, with skipper Virat Kohli at the helm, gave vent to their frustration over the stump mic, which led to a massive uproar. The match officials did have a word with the players concerned but decided not to press the matter further.

AUSSIES OFF TO A WINNING START. 3-time champions Australia kicked off their 2022 Under-19 World Cup campaign in style, defeating hosts West Indies in a pretty convincing manner. First, the bowlers set up the victory with a disciplined bowling display, with as many as three bowlers picking up a 3-fer. And then, with the bat, opener Teague Wyllie struck an unbeaten 86 to hand Australia a couple of crucial points. In the other game, Sri Lanka came back from a precarious position at 99/6 against Scotland to get to 218 first, thanks to Sakuna Liyanage's 85 and then a 5-fer from captain Dunith Wellalage to emerge victorious by 40 runs. There are four groups of 4 teams each, with the top 2 from each group qualifying for the Super League quarter finals. Saturday sees as many as 4 matches - India vs South Africa, Canada vs United Arab Emirates, Ireland vs Uganda and Zimbabwe vs Papua New Guinea. All matches begin at 6.30 pm IST (1300 GMT) but we shall provide exclusive commentary and scoring coverage for the India game. So do not miss to catch the young turks in action.

Aha... Mark Waugh and Brendon Julian manage to catch Marnus Labuschagne for a chat. On the run out to dismiss Rory Burns, Labuschagne says that none of the Aussies in the slip cordon felt it was out and reckoned he held it for a bit too long in his hands. On being asked about how many run outs has he affected in his career, Marnus cannot remember but does remember the one against India last year and a couple in ODIs in 2021. On Head's celebration after taking the catch, ML says that Head calls himself a bin-lid and that celebration was a signature of the same. Now, on his own dismissal yesterday, which has caught social media by storm, Marnus Labuschagne smiles sheepishly but sportingly agrees that he got outside the line and made it for an entertaining view.

So normalcy for England resumes. Overcast conditions, cloudy conditions, sunny conditions, twilight conditions, night-time conditions - does not matter. It always has to be their number 1 batsman, and skipper, Joe Root, to do repair work. He is in early again and in an able partner in Dawid Malan, who has been one of the rare English batsmen to have fought hard in this series, will aim to bat well in the post-Dinner session, which is considered to be the best time to bat in a Day/Night Test. The first ball is scheduled to be bowled at 12.10 pm IST (0640 GMT).

These are lovely conditions to bat. The sun is out. Not too many clouds in the sky. Imagine the pink ball in Mitchell Starc's hands yesterday. Might have well rolled England over in a session or two. But today, he has been struggling because he is searching for swing and it definitely is not present on this ground. The result is he got expensive once again and the pulling back job had to be done by Cummins and Boland. The caught-at-short-leg dismissal of Crawley was a credit to some superb captaincy, with Cummins realizing that there is bounce on this pitch and there are plenty of chances of an inside edge popping towards short leg. Do not remember many series having so many batters caught at short leg.

Another session which started England's way but has ended against them. And they only have themselves to blame. They had Australia at 250-odd for 8, but allowed the tail to wag again, to get to 300. And then, with the bat, with Rory Burns getting a reprieve in the first over itself, with none of the Aussies appealing for a catch, he ended up getting run out needlessly. Crawley's wicket just added salt to their wounds and we head into the Dinner break, with Australia picking up 2 wickets despite the ball doing nothing. Yes, nothing.
Bit more work for Carey again! Cummins bowls it down the leg side. Malan misses the glance and Carey dives down to his right to block it. That is Dinner on Day 2!
This stays a bit low! Length, sixth-stump channel so Malan lets Carey do some work before Dinner and collect it.
Length, on off. Malan blocks it from the crease.
A bumper, outside off. Malan leaves it and Carey leaps to just about stop it.
Nicely played. Fuller, outside off. Root comes down a bit and then works it past mid-wicket. Starc chases and slides to stop it. Three taken.
Length, on middle. This comes back in again. Root misses his defence and gets hit on the thigh. But it does deflect and hits him near the box again!
Length and down the leg side. Malan works it to fine leg for a single.
Boland comes 'round the wicket and bowls it full, outside off. Malan daps it towards gully but the fielder dives and stops it.
A bit wider and fuller this time. Malan makes no attempt to play at it.
Length ball, on off. Malan blocks it with soft hands.
Malan takes a step down the track and taps it to cover.
Full, on off. Blocked out.
Play and a miss! Cummins hurls it fuller, outside off. This shapes away and goes past Root's attempted drive. Brilliant bowling by the Australian skipper to his counterpart.
OUCH! Length, lands on off and comes back in. Root looks to block but gets hit near the box yet again.
Fuller, just outside off. Root taps it to cover.
On a length, outside off. Blocked out.

Big appeal but big inside edge on it! Length, around off. It comes back in sharply as Root looks to block. He gets a big inside edge on the pads but there is a big appeal by all the fielders. Good decision to not review that as there was a big inside edge on that.
On a length, wide enough for Root to leave his first delivery.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out.
Just a touch shorter, outside off. Malan taps it towards point.
Outside off and drawing Malan for the drive. The batter gets it off the inner half to the leg side.
Fuller, on off. Pushed back to the bowler.
Back of a length, around off. Malan blocks it from the crease.
On a length, outside off. Left alone.
The skipper, Joe Root is in at number 4.

OUT! TAKEN! Pat Cummins strikes and gets the wicket of Zak Crawley! The ploy to keep a short leg fielder in place has done wonders for the hosts and England lose their second wicket. Cummins serves a back-of-a-length ball, angling in from middle. Crawley looks to keep it out but it goes off the inside edge and the ball pops up straight towards Travis Head at short leg who takes a sitter. England's trouble with the bat continues!
Commentary.Howout: c Travis Head b Pat Cummins

Commentary.Commentary: A stifled appeal for LBW but the umpire says no! Good-length ball, just outside off. Crawley offers no shot to this one and the ball brushes his pad before going to the keeper.
This is on a length, just outside off. Zak Crawley blocks it to the off side.
Back of a length, around off. Dawid Malan taps it to the off side and takes off for a quick single.

Length ball, around middle. Zak Crawley flicks it past the mid on fielder. Mitchell Starc at mid on gives it a chase and keeps the ball in play by sliding just in front of the ropes. The batters take three runs.
Fuller in length, just outside off. Zak Crawley presses forward and keeps it out.
Good-length delivery, around off. Dawid Malan hops in his crease and defends it.
Back of a length, around off. Dawid Malan blocks it out solidly.
Short of a length, around off. Dawid Malan hangs back to block but it goes off the inside edge towards the leg side.
BEATEN! Fuller in length, well outside off. Dawid Malan gets sucked into the cover drive yet again and the ball goes past his outside edge.
Good-length delivery, around off. Dawid Malan blocks it to the off side.
Boland starts with a length ball, just outside off. Dawid Malan shoulders his arms to it.
First change in bowling. Mitchell Starc is taken off and in comes Scott Boland.
On a length, around off. Zak Crawley blocks it off the front foot.

FOUR! Uppish but it flies past the backward point fielder. Fuller in length, outside off. Zak Crawley looks to drive but it goes off the outside half of the bat past the backward point fielder for a boundary.
Back of a length, outside off. Zak Crawley lets it through to the keeper.
Fuller in length, on middle. Dawid Malan flicks it towards Scott Boland at mid on who fumbles and the ball goes past him. The batters collect a single.
Play and a miss! Length ball, just outside off and shaping away a bit. Dawid Malan looks for a booming drive through the cover region but the ball goes past his blade.
Back of a length, going on with the angle from off. Dawid Malan leaves it alone and the ball goes just over the off stump. Cummins has his hands on his head.
Back of a length, around leg. This is dabbed down towards mid-wicket.

FOUR! Sweet timing again from Zak Crawley. Starc overpitches again as he looks for some swing, which isn't there at the moment. Crawley stands tall and punches it past mid off. Marnus Labuschagne gives chase and puts in the dive but it goes in vain.
On top of middle and defended towards mid on.
Better from Mitchell Starc. On a good length, on off and pushed across the batter. Crawley lets it be.
FOUR LEG BYES! Shorter ball, around leg. Crawley looks to tuck it fine but the ball comes off the hips and does run away fine and into the fence.
FOUR! Starc isn't getting it right here. Sort of a half-volley, around off. Zak Crawley plays a lovely cover drive as he leans into the shot and gets a boundary as well.
Length again, on the pads. Malan looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the thigh pads. Maybe it missed the pads as Malan seems stinged by it.

Close! A length ball, around leg. This one just nips back in a bit and Malan gets rapped on the pads. The hosts appeal but the umpire shakes his head. Probably a touch too high and maybe sliding down leg too.
On off and angling across the left-hander. Malan leaves it alone.
A bit shorter, at the body. Crawley hops back and works it behind square on the leg side for a single.

Peach! Very similar to the previous delivery but even better this time. On a good length, around off and this one just seams away after picthing. Crawley presses forward to block but gets beaten on the outside edge again.
Well bowled! Good-length ball, around off and just holding its line. Crawley looks to block but gets beaten.
Pacy bumper this time, around 142 kph and over off. Malan looks to uppercut it but gets undone by the extra bounce.
FOUR! Nicely put away. A gentle loosener from Starc, fuller and on middle. Dawid Malan works it nicely through mid-wicket and picks up a boundary.
Malan is flirting with balls outside off and that could be dangerous. Slightly fuller, outside off and Malan looks for the cover drive. The ball zips past his outside edge.
Length again, at 144 kph and sliding down the leg side. Malan looks to tuck it away but misses.
Starc goes fuller and at the off stump. Malan punches it nicely towards mid off.
A length ball, outside off and Malan doesn't play at it.
Through the slips! A good-length ball, outside off. Malan has a poke at it and gets the outside edge but luckily for him, the ball goes past third slip and they get a single.
Back of a length, over off. Malan defends it off the back foot but is a bit taken aback by the extra bounce.
Dawid Malan walks in at number 3.

OUT! RUN OUT! Absolutely catastrophic for England and Rory Burns! On off, Zak Crawley presses forward and pushes it towards covers. He wants the single but his partner hesitates a bit. They do go for it in the end but just that split second of hesitation has cost England big time. Marnus Labuschagne picks up the ball and hits the stumps at the batter's end. The third umpire is called in and the replay shows that Burns does not have any part of his bat inside the crease. Well, he doesn't get off the hook twice.
Commentary.Howout: run out (Marnus Labuschagne)

Commentary.Commentary: Is that a run out? The leg umpire has sent it upstairs and Burns seems to be in trouble here! The replays roll in and it shows that Rory Burns is just short of his crease. A direct hit from Marnus Labuschagne and Burns will have to take the long walk back to the pavilion.
Sliding down leg, Crawley misses the flick.
England are away. Length again, on off and this is nudged through gully with soft hands for a couple.
A length ball, outside off and nipping in. Crawley leaves it alone.
Who will bowl from the other end? It is the Aussie skipper, Pat Cummins.

Beaten! Good length, just around the off pole and the ball zips past the outside edge as Burns looks to block. There was a huge noise though but no one went up. A maiden to start with from Mitchell Starc. UltraEdge shows that there was a huge nick but surprisingly no one heard it.
Too close for comfort! A cross-seamer, around the top of off. Rory Burns goes back to defend and almost ends up chopping it back onto the stumps.
A fuller delivery this time, at 144 kph and outside off. Burns just watches it go past him.
Back of a length, around off. Rory Burns defends it off the back foot.
An appeal for LBW but the umpire is not interested! This is a length ball, jagging back in late from off. Burns misses his flick and gets rapped on his pad. That would have certainly gone down leg.
Back of a length, around off. Rory Burns stays back and blocks it out to the off side.

We are back, folks! The Aussie players have taken the field for one final innings in the series. Out walk Rory Burns and Zak Crawley. Burns with his hair flowing as he hasn't tied it up. Mitchell Starc is set to steam in, with the pink ball, under lights. Jeez, that sounds scary! Here we go...
... Fourth Innings ...

Right then, the visitors need 271 runs to pull off a big victory here and they have all the time they need to get there. But it has never been an issue of time and rather an issue of lack of skill and grit from the English batters. The Aussie pace attack will be pumped up and with the lights on, it will be difficult for the batters. Can England somehow find some inspiration and just hang out there in the middle? Still more than 55 overs left in the day and we wouldn't bet against this one ending tonight itself. Stay tuned for the chase.

Australia came into Day 3 with three top-order batters back in the hut and lost another three wickets pretty early on as Smith and Head couldn't make an impact. The lower-middle order yet again showed grit and determination as Carey and Green put on a nice stand of 49 to stretch the lead over 200. After Green fell, Carey carried on and was supported well by Cummins. Carey though got lucky on more than a couple of occasions and fell just a run short of what would have been a really well-compiled half-century. In the end, Australia have managed to take the lead well over 250 runs and they will feel confident of winning this one as well.

England have finally managed to bundle out Australia for 155 runs and they have to chase down 271 runs in order to end this torrid tour on a good note. Their bowlers have been out there bowling on almost every single day of the series and the batters need to show their class and back up the bowling effort. Wood has certainly been the pick of the bowlers as he ended with 6 for 37, his career-best figures. Broad too was fantastic and the bowling unit can be pleased with that effort.

OUT! CASTLED! Career-best figures for Mark Wood! Finally, it feels like he has been rewarded for his efforts! Length ball, on off. Cummins goes for the massive heave but connects only with the thin air around his bat. The ball shatters the stumps. Wood leads his team off the field and soaks in the applause from this Hobart crowd. That ends the innings and Australia are bowled out for 155!
Commentary.Howout: b Mark Wood

Commentary.Commentary: Short and down the leg side. Cummins misses the pull. A polite inquiry by Wood to the umpire but nothing doing.
Cummins backs away to the leg side so Wood fires it full and wide outside off. Cummins fails to dig it out.
Length, around off. Tapped towards gully.
Full, on off. Driven down the ground again but Broad dives and stops it.

Two more! Length, on off. Lyon thumps it down the ground. past the dive of Broad. Burns dives from mid off but gets his knee on the ball. It is deflected away and the batters get a couple before the fielder cuts it off.
A huge cheer as Lyon gets off the mark! Full, on middle. He works it towards deep backward square leg for a couple.
Length, outside off. Lyon misses the drive.
Nathan Lyon is the last man in for Australia.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! GONE THIS TIME! After surviving a couple of close calls, Alex Carey walks off on 49! He batted well though. Made those reprives count and put on a good recovery towards the end. This is full and way, way outside off. Carey goes at it with his hands only. The ball goes past the inside edge and there is a faint edge. Billings takes a good low catch and there is an appeal. Carey stands his ground for a moment but walks off just after the finger is raised. No review this time!
Commentary.Howout: c Sam Billings b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: A single now! Short and on off. Carey taps it towards cover for an easy singe. He moves to 49.
Length ball, on middle. Carey gets the inside edge past short leg. They don't take the single though.
Shorter, around off. Carey taps it towards point. He thinks off a single for a moment but decides against it in the end.
Wood comes 'round the wicket and bowls a length ball, down the leg side. Carey leaves it.
Bumper on the body and Carey sits under it.
Shorter, outside off. Left alone by Carey.
Short of a length, on off. Cummins rises and taps it towards cover.
Short and on the body. Cummins sits under it.
Nicely driven by Carey to deep cover. 150 up for Australia and the lead is 265. Carey moves to 48 too.
On a length, on off. Cummins taps it past cover for one.
On a length, outside off. Left alone.
Length ball, on off. Cummins blocks it off the front foot.
Back of a length, wide enough for Carey to leave it.
Short again, down the leg side. Left alone by Carey.
FOUR! Lovely stroke! Short and just outside off. Carey backs away a bit and then carves it over covers for a boundary.
Back of a length, wide outside off. Carey leaves it.
This time Carey sits under the ball. Watch out for the yorker probably.
Bumper down the leg side. Carey leaves it with ease by moving inside the line of the ball.
Fuller, on off. Cummins blocks it off the front foot.
Broad goes full, angling away. Carey taps it past cover for one.
Fuller, on off. Carey is once again solid in blocking it.
Nice and full, on off. Carey gets forward to block it.
Back of a length, around off and blocked out.
Well played. Shorter and angling across off. Carey punches it to deep backward point for a couple.
Stuart Broad (15-2-42-2) to resume from the other end.
On a length for the first time in the over. Outside off and Cummins is beaten while looking to block.
Nicely done by Cummins as he ducks under this one well.
On the body again. Cummins gets hit on the pads and it rolls to the leg side.
Back of a length, around off. Cummins hops up to block but is beaten.
OUCH! That will sting! Short and on the body. Cummins looks to duck but he does so very awkwardly. The ball misses the bat and hits his arm.
Bumper, on middle. Cummins gets hit on the pad but it baloons and falls short of short leg.

We are back for the post-Dinner session! 67 overs left in the day and an extra 8 overs if there's a possibility of a result tonight itself. Pat Cummins and Alex Carey take guard. Mark Wood is ready to steam in.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

Now then. We have 8 more sessions of cricket lined up and there will definitely be a result in this game. If England can get these two wickets quickly, they might have a chance of chasing down the total and go home with a win. But for that, they need to get a wicket first. Will they be able to? Or will Australia's tail wag again? Join us at 12:10 pm IST (6:40 am GMT) to find out!

The day started with Broad and Wood bowling in tandem. Broad bowled well, got a few balls to go past the bat, got in a few LBW calls but did not get a wicket. That was not the matter for Wood though. He kept coming hard at the batters and picked up 3 early wickets to dismantle the Australian middle order. The hosts were 63 for 6 and in big trouble. But then something happened that arrested their slide. Carey was bowled off the bowling of Woakes but the TV umpire decided that the bowler had overstepped. That was the luck that Carey needed and he put on a 49-run stand with Green. Just when it looked like these two batters will see the session off for Australia, Broad came back for his second spell. The veteran pacer made the ball talk under lights and got the wicket of Green. Wood came back and got a wicket but was denied the wicket of Cummins by millimeters again as Ball Tracker had the ball just missing the off pole.

What a session of Test cricket! 5 wickets for England but Australia have scored 104 runs in the session. They lead by 256 at this point and the lead will go up by a bit at the very least in the next session. They also had luck going their way in this session with Carey getting bowled once but Woakes overstepping, with Carey given LBW but Ball Tracker showing that the ball pitched outside leg by millimeters and once with Cummins given out LBW but the ball missing the off pole by millimeters again! England needed some luck going their way in this game but that has not happened. They have bowled extremely well though and would look to finish the Australian tail quickly.

FOUR! Well played by Carey and Australia end the session on a high. Around middle and leg, this is flicked through mid-wicket for a boundary. At the Dinner interval, Australia are 141/8 and they lead by 256 runs.
Vicious bounce this time from Broad! Banged in, around off. Cummins is taken aback by it. He still manages to keep it down on the leg side and even picks up a single.

The lead now goes past 250 and with every run scored, England will be feeling more and more anxious. Good-length ball, pushed across the left-hander. Carey edges it down towards the third man fence and picks up three runs.
Good running! The man at mid off was right on the edge of the circle and Cummins takes advantage of that. Slightly fuller, on off and driven on the up towards mid off for a single.
A length ball, on off. Cummins makes a bit of room and swats it across towards dep mid-wicket. Woakes runs around from the square leg fence and keeps it down to a couple.
Right around the top of off. Pat Cummins stays solid in defense.
Just wide! Short of a good length, on the body. Cummins hops and tucks it just past short leg for another single.
Wood looks to bounce Carey out with a quick bumper. Carey though does well to get inside the line and pulls it along the ground towards fine leg for a single.
Attempted short ball, down the leg side. Carey lets it go past him.
Carey backs away and Wood follows him with a length ball. Carey looks to heave it away to the leg side but gets an inside edge back onto the pads.

Ouch! That looked nasty! A quick short ball, angled at the body. Cummins tries to fend it away but gets hit flush on the left glove. The ball pops up and falls safely around leg gully. They get a run.

FOUR! Well played and that's valuable runs for the hosts. Back of a length, angled across the right-hander. Cummins hangs deep and just opens the face of the bat to guide it towards the backward point fence.
This one is sliding onto the pads, Cummins looks to flick but gets it off the inner half of the bat towards square leg. They cross for one and look for the second but don't go for it.
On a good length, around off. Cummins hangs back to block it on the off side.
Back of a length, around off and seaming back in. Cummins looks to defend off the back foot but gets a blow around the chest area.
A length ball, angled into middle and leg. Cummins defends it off the front foot.
Fullish ball, around off and pushed out on the off side.
There's still a lot of movement off the pitch here. A length ball, outside off and this one shapes in late and just goes past the off stump as Cummins makes the leave.
Wood comes over the wicket now and angles in a short ball, on the body. Cummins hops and keeps it down towards square leg for a single.
Another one that is full and fast, across the off stump. It is a bit wider this time but Cummins can't get any bat on it.
And again! Short and outside leg. Cummins isn't interested in playing at that one.
Shorter in length, down the leg side. Left alone.

Pat Cummins is given out LBW and he has reviewed it. UltraEdge confirms that there's certainly no bat involved. Ball Tracker shows that the ball was angling across the off stump and missing. The decision is overturned. Another excellent review and Cummins is having a laugh out there.

NOT OUT! Missing the off stump by millimeters and Australia get lucky yet again! Cummins has a nice laugh about it but none of the English players are smiling. Corker of a yorker by Wood though. He comes 'round the wicket with Cummins probably expecting a short one. Cummins is already ducking a bit and Wood fires a yorker, right on the boot. Cummins fails to dig it out and gets hit on the boot. Up goes the finger but Cummins reviews it! No bat on that again, but since Wood is bowling 'round the stumps, the angle could take the ball away from the off pole. Yes, it is! Missing off stump by millimeters. Not even clipping the stump!
The skipper, Pat Cummins, is in at number 10.

OUT! TAKEN! No review needed this time and the workhorse, Wood, gets his third 5-wicket haul in Tests! He has been a sensational bowler for England and has deserved each and every one of these wickets! He soaks in the applause from the crowd and Australia lose their eighth wicket. A bumper, on the body of Starc. He looks to block but gets the inside edge on the thigh pad and straight to short leg. Ollie Pope takes it with ease.
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Pope b Mark Wood

Commentary.Commentary: Full, on off. Pushed back to the bowler.
Length, on off. Blocked out.
Length ball, on the pads. Worked through square leg for a couple.

Alex Carey is given out LBW but he has reviewed it. It is close to the bat but UltraEdge confirms that there is no bat involved. Ball Tracker builds up and half of the ball is pitching outside leg. Maybe a bit more than half and luckily for Carey that's enough. The decision is overturned.

NOT OUT! Pitching outside leg! Celebrappeal does not work for Broad this time and Carey gets lucky again! Length ball, landing around leg. Carey looks to block but gets hit on the pads. Broad is running in celebration already and the umpire raises the finger! But Carey reviews it. No bat on that. But, but, the ball is pitching just outside leg. Just outside leg and by that I mean millimeters outside leg! All that Root can do is have a wry smile.
Length ball, outside off. Carey pushes it wide of gully for a single.
Length, on the paads. Starc works it past square leg for one.
A nasty bumper, on the body. Carey gets hit on the gloves as he looks to block awkwardly and the ball falls around short leg.
Shorter ball, outside off. Carey works it past point for a couple.
Back of a length, on off. Blocked out.

Review not taken! Shorter and down the leg side. Carey looks to work it away but misses. There is a noise as the ball goes past him and Billings takes it. An appeal follows from the keeper and the bowler but the umpire is unmoved. The English players get together but Stokes from square leg yells 'JUMPER! JUMPER!' to suggest that it hit the sweater of Carey. Good decision as the replays confirm the same.
Short and down the leg side, left alone. A rare mistake by Billings as he fails to gather the ball after diving to his right. Bye taken.
Short of a length, on middle. Carey taps it past square leg for a single.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out.
Mitchell Starc is the new man in.

OUT! LBW! Broad finally gets his man! He has deserved a wicket for the way he has bowled this morning! The 49-run stand is broken and England needed this big time. Length ball, on off. Green gets forward to block but the ball nips away a bit and Green gets hit on the pads. Broad puts on a celebrappeal - meaning that he is celebrating even before the decision is made! But the umpire is not convinced and there are also overthrows when someone throws the ball and misses the stumps. Root decides to review this one. No bat on that and Ball Tracker has the ball smashing into the off pole after hitting in line!
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: Ooh, seems close! Huge appeal for LBW and Joe Root has gone for the review. UltraEdge shows that there's no bat involved. Ball Tracker confirms that the ball does hit Green in line and is going to hit the off stump. Brilliant review and this might just open the floodgates for England.
On a length, around off. Green works it to mid-wicket.
Nicely pushed to mid off.
On a length, outside off. Left alone.
Full, on the pads. Flicked away nicely to deep mid-wicket for one.
Stuart Broad (11-2-24-1) is back on.

FOUR! And yet another boundary down to third man! Full, around off. Green gets the outside edge again. This time the ball goes along the ground and past the slip cordon for a boundary. Frustration is clearly visible on the face of Woakes.
Short of a length, outside off. Left alone.
Beaten again! Fuller, fifth-stump line. Green looks to drive it away but it zips past the outside edge.
Nicely driven down the ground but the man at mid off dives and stops it.
FOUR! More runs to third man and no luck for England! Length ball, on off. Green gets the outside edge but it drops just short of the man at second slip and runs to the fence.
Fuller, on middle and leg. Blocked out by Green.
Full, on off. Blocked out to mid off.
Nicely played. Length, just outside off. Carey nicely works it past backward point for a couple.
Jaffa! Fuller, angling across off. Carey looks to work it away to the leg side but is beaten.
On a length, around off. Carey blocks it out.
Shorter, outside off. Slapped towards cover.
Length, on off. Tapped to the leg side.
A solid front-foot defence by Green to end the over.
On a length, around off. Blocked out.
Full, on off. Pushed down the ground. Woakes gets his right hand down and gets his hand to it and half-stops it.
Again! On a length, just outside off. Green takes a stride forward to block and it goes past the outside edge.
Beaten again! Fuller, around off. Green goes for the drive but it zips past the outside edge.
Length, around off. Green gets the inside edge on the pads.
On a good length this time, outside off. Carey taps it towards point. A maiden over from Robinson.
A length ball, on off. Carey taps it back onto the deck.
Lovely delivery! Perfect length, on off and angling away from the left-hander. Carey has a poke at it but the ball zips past the outside edge.
Robinson goes fuller, around off and middle. Carey is brought forward to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Right around the top of off. Blocked out off the back foot.
A touch fuller, on off. Carey defends it back to the bowler.
A length ball, around leg. Carey looks to tuck it away but gets it off the inner half of the bat towards backward square leg. They get one.
On off. Blocked out.
Over middle, Green stands tall and works it through mid-wicket for a single. The 100 is up for Australia now and the lead is stretched to 215 already.
Full and straight, Green punches it back towards the bowler who does well to get his hand to it.
On a good length, angled into off and this one holds its line after pitching. Green makes a watchful block off the back foot.
A length ball, at the hips. Green tucks it around the corner and picks up a couple down to deep square leg.
Length, on off. Carey takes a step down the track to block it out.
Beaten! This lands on a length, on off and comes back in a bit. Carey is beaten on the inside edge while looking to block.
Nicely defended out by Carey again.
Fuller, on off. Carey goes for the drive but gets the inside edge on the pads.
On a length, angling across off. Left alone.
Fuller, on off. Blocked back to the bowler.
Slightly shorter, around off and worked past backward point for one.
Edged away! Back of a length, around off. Cameron Green hops back to defend but gets a thick outside edge past the slip cordon. The fielder chases it down but they come back for the third.
A length ball, around off and angling in. Green strides forward to defend.
Woakes goes fuller, on off. Carey pushes it past mid off for a single.
On a good length, around off and kept out by Carey.

NO BALL! Big, big moment in the match but the rub of the green goes Carey's way. A shortish ball, around off. Alex Carey looks to pull but sort of falls over and ends up getting an inside edge back onto the stumps. The third umpire checks for a no ball and unfortunately for England, Chris Woakes doesn't have anything behind the line and the visitors cannot believe it. A huge let off.

OH! They are checking for the no ball now. Very, very close. Reckon Woakes has overstepped. Checking, checking, checking and NO BALL! A loud cheer from the crowd as Carey walks back to the crease! Stokes cannot believe it! The side-on angle made it look quite close but the stump camera showed that foot of Woakes had just landed over the crease. Still, a very close call.
Around off. Defended off the front foot.
A length ball, around off. Carey works it towards covers and sets off for a quick single.
A touch fuller again, on middle. Carey defends it out solidly.
Beaten! Robinson goes fuller, on off and the ball's going across. Carey is pushed forward as he looks to keep it out and the ball whizzes past the outside edge.
Robinson hits the length hard, on middle. Carey hangs back to block.
A length ball, on off and sliding across. Carey presses forward to defend.
Back of a length, around the hips. Carey pulls it past short leg.

Drinks! A really good session so far for England but Australia already have a pretty decent lead. The next hour of play is crucial with the ball seaming a bit. If England can get a couple of wickets before Dinner, it will make for a very interesting game.
Woakes goes fuller, around off. Carey drives it to sweeper cover for a single.
On off. Blocked out on the off side.
Almost chopped on! On a good length, around the off pole. Carey looks to stride forward but gets an inside edge back onto the pads.
In that channel around off and beating the bat of Carey.
FOUR! And again! A tad too full, around off. Carey drives it through cover-point this time and the ball races away to the fence.

FOUR! Carey gets a juicy half-volley, outside off and he is able to stroke it away through covers for another boundary. Australia's lead reaches 200 now. An interesting phase coming up now. Wonder how the Aussies will approach the game now. Anything over 250 could be a big task for England to chase in the final innings.
FOUR! That will release a lot of pressure. On the pads and flicked away fine by Green into the fine leg fence.
Fuller delivery, on off. Carey prods and pushes it on the off side for a quick single. There should not have been a run there to be honest.
On a good length, wide of off stump. Green taps it on the off side and picks up a quick single.
Length again, outside off. Green shoulders arms.
Around middle and leg, Carey strides forward to defend but gets an inside edge past short leg. They get a single.
Well bowled. Fullish ball, on off and sliding across the left-hander. Carey looks to push at it but the ball zips past the outside edge.
A touch fuller, around off and nipping in late. Green makes the leave. A maiden over from Woakes.
Around the off pole and blocked out.
That's the second time Green's got an inside edge onto the pads and there's not a fielder for bat-pad yet. A good-length ball, around off and Green looks to block but inside edges it onto the pads.
Slightly fuller, around off and nipping in late. Green makes a leave.
Right around the top of off and nipping back in sharply. Green looks to defend off the front foot but gets an inisde edge onto the pads.
Good-length ball, around off and nipping in off the seam. Green looks to defend but gets hit high on the pads as the ball goes towards the slip cordon.

'Not far away here, boys' Sam Billings has said that quite a few times this morning. He certainly is enjoying his debut Test and has provided England with some much-needed energy that they were lacking in the last few games.
On off. This is pushed towards the cover region.
Good-length ball, on leg. Carey works it behind square on the leg side for a couple.
Just a fraction short, on middle. Green tucks it through square leg and picks up a single.
Slightly fuller, angled into middle. Green defends it solidly off the back foot.
A length ball, outside off and left alone by Green.
Pitched up, on off. This is punched back towards the bowler.
Banged in from 'round the stumps and going over middle. Carey ducks under it.
What was Carey looking to do there? Carey shuffles right across his stumps and Wood fires in a quick, fuller delivery around middle. Carey just about manages to keep it out on the leg side.
Wood comes from 'round the wicket this time and angles a short ball at the body. Green hops and keeps it down towards backward square leg for a single.
On a good length, angled into middle and at 144 kph. Green gets right behind the line of the ball to block.
Wood hits the length hard and bowls it around the off pole. Green dabs it down towards covers.
Back of a length, around off and angling across. Carey hangs deep and bunts it down on the off side for a quick single. Green once again hesitates but they get through for one.
Full, on off. Pushed past covers for a couple. Nicely played by Green there.
On a length, outside off. Left alone.

A length ball, around middle and leg. Carey flicks it to the left of mid on. Stuart Broad over there makes a really good stop and gets in the direct hit at the bowler's end. The batters though cross over comfortably.
Fuller, on off. Worked to mid on.
Full, on the pads. Flicked to fine leg for a couple.
Ollie Robinson (4-2-5-0) is back into the attack.
Full, on off. Blocked out.

Would have been a run out! Wood comes 'round the wicket and bowls a length ball, on middle. Carey works it to the leg side and sets off. Green though is watching the ball and is very slow to react. The man at mid-wicket moves to his left, gathers the ball and has a shy at the batter's end. The ball misses the stumps though. Green would have been out had the ball hit.
Another short one and Carey ducks.
Bumper, on off. Carey ducks under it.
Short ball, down the leg side. Left alone.
Alex Carey is in at number 8. No slips for him. Not a single one. Clearly, the English are looking to bounce him out. Interesting tactics to a new batter.

OUT! TAKEN! GONE GONE GONE! Smith is gone and Wood is delighted! I would be too if I got Smith out and took 4 wickets against the Aussies! But Wood has been sensational with the ball and he has deserved this. One would say that he has deserved a lot more wickets but hasn't got them! The barrage of short deliveries continues from Wood and he bowls a sharp one at Smith's body. Smith shuffles a bit inside the line looking to pull but he can't keep it on the ground as he gets the top edge. The ball goes straight to fine leg and Dawid Malan takes an easy catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Dawid Malan b Mark Wood

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length, outside off. Pushed to covers.
Full, on the pads. Worked away past square leg for one.

Appeal again by Broad! Length and on the pads. Green gets hit on the pads but it is likely sliding down the leg stump and could be too high too. It rolls away to the leg side and the batters cross over. Broad puts in a toned-down appeal this time but the umpire says no.

Well bowled! Length ball, landing on off and coming back in. Green leaves a gap between his bat and pad. The ball sneaks through that and hits him on the pads. Broad appeals yet again but not given. Ball Tracker shows it was going way over the off stumps.
On a length, outside off. Left alone.
Fired full, on middle. Smith works it past square leg for a single.
On a length, on off. Smith blocks it out.
A bumper, down the leg side. Green ducks under it yet again. A really good over by Wood!
This time Green ducks low enough to let the ball go over him.
Wood comes 'round the stumps and bowls a short one, on off. Green gets low but not low enough. The ball hits his shoulder.
Too short and down the leg side. Green lets it go way over him. Billings gets to his left to gather it. Wide called. That was too high!
Length ball, on off. Blocked out.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Wood gets his third! It is Broad who is going past the edges, getting the ball to hit the batters on the pads and Wood is reaping the rewards with his short bowling! A short one, down the leg side. Head shuffles a bit inside the line to work it away but gets a faint tickle on it. There is a noise as the ball passes the bat and Billings does the rest behind the stumps. The umpire obliges this time and gives Head his marching orders. A really good morning for England so far but they will need to finish this off quickly. Cameron Green is the new man at the crease.
Commentary.Howout: c Sam Billings b Mark Wood

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length, around off. Tapped to covers.
Length and around leg. Head gets struck on the pads as he misses his glance. The ball rolls away to the leg side and the batters get a leg bye. A mild appeal again, but this is pitching outside leg.
Play and a miss! Broad drags his length back a bit and angles it across off. Head goes for the drive but is beaten on the outside edge.
Full and a bit wider. Head drives it uppishly, to the left of deep cover for a couple.
Length, outside off. Left alone.

Fired full, on the pads. Smith misses the flick and gets hit on the pads. There is a bit of an appeal by Broad but he suggests that there was a bit of bat on it. Good call as the umpire gives it as runs and the replays confirm the same. Billings has a burst of energy and has a few words of encouragement for the bowler.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.
Wood is back to banging it short, on middle. Head blocks it well.
Very full and around leg. Head looks to flick it away but gets hit on the pads. There is a mild appeal but it was pitching outside leg.
Well bowled! A bumper, on the body again. Head hops up looking to work it away but gets hit on the shoulder of the bat. It lands near him though and doesn't pop up.
A sharp short one, on the body. Head ducks under it though.
Short and on the body. Smith pulls it along the ground to deep square leg for one.
On a length, on off. Blocked out.
Beaten! A touch shorter and angling across off. Head is stuck in the crease while looking to block and the ball zips past the outside edge.
FOUR! Top shot! Full by Broad again, on off. Head nicely punches it down the ground. Broad dives to his left but cannot get there and the ball runs to the fence.
Stays a bit low! Length ball, angling across off. Head goes for the cut but misses it. The ball dies down on its way to the keeper.
Full, on middle. Smith gets it off the inner half past square leg for one. 50 up for the hosts.
On a length, just outside off. Smith blocks it from the crease.
Length ball, around off. Head drives it to deep cover for one.
Length ball, around off. Smith blocks it with ease.
Back of a length again, on the body. Head works it towards square leg for one.
Short of a length, on the body. Head works it aerially towards where a short leg would have been. But there is no one there.
Travis Head walks out at number 6.

OUT! TAKEN! Gone this time! A faint edge and Scott Boland has to walk back! Well bowled by Wood. He bowls a bumper, right at the body. It is a rising one too and too good for the nightwatchman. Boland looks to keep it out but gets a thin edge back to the keeper. Billings does it with ease and Boland's resilience ends. He has done his job well though.
Commentary.Howout: c Sam Billings b Mark Wood

Commentary.Commentary: Bumper, on off. Boland sits under it.
Back of a length, on off. Blocked out.

Big appeal again! Ooh, this is much closer! This time Broad goes full and around off. Smith rarely misses these balls but twice in the same over, he gets struck on the pads while looking to work it away. Broad is convinced again, well he always is convinced! But to be fair, this is a good appeal. The umpire turns it down again and Root after thinking about it for a while, decides not to review. Impact could have been an issue there.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.

He misses this time! Broad looked very excited about that but Root reckons it was too high! Length ball, lands on middle. Smith misses the flick and gets hit near the knee roll. There is a big appeal by Broad and he looks convinced but the umpire is not. Root walks up to have a word with the pacer but the English skipper reckons that it is too high and decides not to review. Good decision as Ball Tracker shows that it was going over.
FOUR! Nicely done by Smith! Broad goes full and targets the pads in the hope that Smith will miss it. But Smith clips it nicely and the ball races to the square leg fence.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Smith goes for the drive with his hands but gets a thick inside edge back on the pads.
Length, on middle and leg. Smith misses the flick and gets hit on the pads.
Length, on the pads. Smith works it past mid-wicket for a single.

Full and wide outside off. Boland goes for the drive but gets the outside edge. The ball flies very low to the left of Burns at gully. He dives that side and gets his hands to the ball. Don't think that carried to him. The ball is deflected away and the batters take one.
On a length, on off. Blocked out.

The batters run four! Full, on middle. Boland nicely punches it down the ground. But the ball slows down as it approaches the fence. Broad gives the long chase to stop the ball just inside the ropes. But the batters have enough time to run four!
A bumper by Wood but way down the leg side. Boland leaves it and Billings moves to his left to collect it.
Wood hurls a length ball, on off. Boland stays in the crease to block it out.
Mark Wood to steam in from the opposite end.
Maiden to start the day. Length ball, around off. Smith looks to work it away to the leg side but gets it off the outer half back to the bowler.
Nice and full, on off. Smith pushes it to mid on.
This is fuller, just outside off. Smith prods forward and taps it towards mid off.
Another one that shapes away from the sixth stump. Smith is yet to offer a stroke on Day 3.
A bit of away shape on that but this starts way outside off. Smith shoulders arms yet again.
Broad starts with a length ball, landing wide outside off and coming back in. Smith leaves it alone though.
We are ready for play! The overnight batters, Steven Smith and Scott Boland make their way out to the middle. Stuart Broad to start proceedings with the ball on Day 3. Let's play...

In some big news coming out of India, Virat Kohli has decided to step down as the Test skipper of the side after an illustrious phase at the helm. He led India in 68 Tests out of which the team won 50 games with a win percentage of just under 60. This makes Kohli the most successful Test skipper for India to date and this includes taking the team to number 1 ranking and to the final of the inaugural WTC. Now that Kohli has decided to hang his boots and focus on his batting more, it will be interesting to see who takes over as the skipper of the side.

It was the same old story for the visitors on Day 2 as all the early inroads made by them just slipped away and they ended up conceding more runs than they should have. The batting, well it was as poor as it has been throughout the series and in about two sessions of play, England were bundled out. Their pacers though bowled their heart out late in the day and have managed to put their team in a position from which they can at least allow themselves a chance in this match. So, will the English bowlers get those early breakthroughs and make a contest out of this one? Or will the hosts manage to consolidate a decent lead and put the visitors out of their misery yet again? We'll find out soon.

Australia lead by 152 runs and just like the first innings, have lost 3 early wickets. The pair of Steven Smith and Scott Boland did tremendously well to fend off an on-song English attack late in the day and they will now look to utilize the afternoon to get that lead past at least 250. We have already seen what the pink ball can do late in the evening and the Aussies will want to take advantage while conditions are better for batting.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 3 of the fifth and final Ashes Test at the Bellerive Oval. Day 2 had no rain but there was cloud cover and it certainly was a day dominated by bowlers. As many as 17 wickets fell and if that is anything to go by then we can expect a lot of action today as well. The weather looks to be perfect throughout the day and it should be better for batting early in the afternoon. Let's see which side can come out of the blocks quickly and seize their opportunities.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

Right then! Day 3 is known as the moving day in Test cricket but it might just be the final day of the 2021-22 Ashes series as well. With the English bowlers keeping their team in the match, it is set up really nicely and whichever team makes an early start on Day 3, will hold the advantage. Do join us on the 16th for Day 3's live action. The first ball will be bowled at 9:00 am IST (3:30 am GMT). But as you all know, the buildup will begin well in advance. So make sure you join us for the same. Till then, take care and goodbye!

England did not have the best of days with the bat, which has been the case for them for the entire series but they their bowlers have bent their backs and made sure that they are still in the game. They managed to bowl out Australia for 303 in the first innings but their batters failed to put on a show at Hobart. Their openers, Crawley and Burns fell cheaply and it was once again the pair of Root and Malan who had to do the repair work. They did manage to steady the ship but both of them perished in quick succession and the English side was sent on the back foot. If not for the tailenders contribution at the fag end, England would have failed to go past even the 150-run mark. However, the tourists needed to get early breakthroughs with the ball, and boy have they delivered! Broad set the tone upfront and got rid of the dangerous David Warner for a pair. Woakes also made the pink ball talk and he got the prized wicket of Marnus Labuschagne, although it wasn't the best of deliveries. Wood bowled his heart out and got the wicket of Usman Khawaja with an unplayable bumper. The English bowlers have done a good job on Day 2 and they must ensure that they restrict the hosts to a chaseable target on Day 3.

The Aussies started the day at 241/6 and the GOAT, Nathan Lyon played a crucial cameo to take his team past the 300-run mark. The Aussies followed it up with a brilliant bowling peformance  and bundled out the tourists for just 188. Their skipper, Pat Cummins, led from the front and finished with 4 wickets to his name. All the Aussie bowlers executed their plans to perfection and they were so accurate that Cummins did not even bowl his spinner, Nathan Lyon for one over. Starc, the pink-ball specialist, wasn't at his very best but he managed to grab 3 wickets in the end. The Aussies had a tricky period of play to negotiate and the English bowlers made things hard for them. David Warner was sent back for a pair and Labuschagne also followed suit after scoring just 5 runs. Khawaja and Smith tried to steady the innings but Khawaja got an unplayable delivery from Wood and his resistance came to an end. Scott Boland joined Steven Smith as a night watchman and he ensured that the Aussies do not lose any more wickets.

Wow! What a riveting day's play we have witnessed at the Bellerive Oval. As many as 17 wickets fell in the day and this Test is tantalizingly poised now. The English bowlers have done well to get wickets under the floodlights after the tourists were bundled out for just 188 in the first innings.

Boland survives! Well bowled and well played! Mark Wood puts everything in this last delivery and gets in the yorker on middle at 145 kph. Scott Boland just about manages to get his bat down in time to jam it out towards short leg. A brilliant end to the day as Australia finish the day on 36/3 and they lead by 152 runs.
Just short! A fiery bumper, around middle and leg. The ball hurries onto Boland as he looks to keep it at bay. The ball hits the gloves and loops up but falls well short of leg gully.
Well played by Boland. On a good length, angled at the body and Boland manages to keep it down.
A length ball, on middle and Boland gets bat on it yet again.
Back of a length, around middle and leg. Boland manages to keep it down.

That is a sore one! A spicy short ball, on the body. Boland tries his best to fend it away but gets hit flush on the index finger. He seems to be in some pain but the physio isn't out on the field. The physio does eventually come out but the umpire sends him back as he feels the batter is trying to make the most of it.
